{
  "type": "Subnet",
  "title": "Subnet",
  "description": "A subnet is a range of IP addresses within a VPC, scoped to a single Availability Zone. Subnets are either public (routed to an Internet Gateway) or private (routed through a NAT Gateway or isolated).",
  "connections": {
    "parents": [
      "VPC"
    ],
    "trafficSources": [],
    "trafficTargets": [],
    "associations": [
      "RouteTable"
    ]
  },
  "practices": [
    "Use subnets across multiple Availability Zones for high availability.",
    "A subnet is public only if its associated route table has a route to an Internet Gateway.",
    "Private subnets should route outbound traffic through a NAT Gateway, not directly to an IGW.",
    "Don't place all resources in a single subnet \u2014 separate by tier (web, app, data) for security."
  ],
  "configNotes": [
    "CIDR block is required and must fall within the parent VPC's CIDR range.",
    "Availability Zone is required and cannot be changed after creation."
  ],
  "example": {
